                        "content": "A client with an anxiety disorder is taking buspirone (BuSpar) orally. The client tells the nurse that it is difficult to swallow the tablets. Which is the best instruction to provide to the client?",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "80db17ea97ed8fdcd1b6b9666390fca1",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Applying 应用",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nBuspirone may be administered without regard to meals, and the tablets may be crushed. Mixing the tablet uncrushed in apple sauce will not ensure ease in swallowing. This medication is not available in liquid form. It is premature to advise the client to call the primary health care provider (PHCP) for a change in medication without first trying alternative interventions.\n\nClient Needs: Physiological Integrity\nClinical Judgment/Cognitive Skill(s): Take Action\nCognitive Ability: Applying\nContent Area: Pharmacology: Psychiatric: Antianxiety/Anxiolytics\nHealth Problem: Mental Health: Anxiety Disorder\nIntegrated Process: Nursing Process/Implementation\nPriority Concepts: Safety, Patient Education\nStrategies: Strategic Words, Subject\n\nTest-Taking Strategy:\nNote the strategic word, best. Focus on the subject, buspirone. Doing so will help you recognize that the medication can be crushed, making it easier to swallow, because it is not available in liquid form. Eliminate any option that doesn't make swallowing easier. Remember that interventions can be instituted before the PHCP is called.",
                        "id": "1f5d8c1a67354133a7f1e8e6e82f35af",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
